Erwin Moller&#39;s suggestions are all good suggestions and all easily implementable. I think those are the best way(s) to go about it, but if you don&#39;t want to use any of those methods, then you could relay a `$_GET` variable from one redirect to another in either a plain message or a value that represents a message:

    $red_url = &#39;http://www.example.com/?msg=Password+has+been+reset&#39;;
    header(&quot;Location: {$red_url}&quot;);
    exit;

Make sure to use something like `htmlspecialchars()` or equivalent when outputting the message. This would take care of malicious code insertion, but this method still allows the end user the most flexibility to mess with your site messaging.

The variable method would be similar:

    $red_url = &#39;http://www.example.com/?msg=1234&#39;;
    header(&quot;Location: {$red_url}&quot;);
    exit;

on the display page use some way to fetch or translate the `msg` code:

    &lt;?php if(!empty($_GET[&#39;msg&#39;]) &amp;&amp; is_numeric($_GET[&#39;msg&#39;])): ?&gt;
    &lt;h3 class=&quot;site-message&quot;&gt;&lt;?php echo myCodeToMessageFunc($_GET[&#39;msg&#39;]) ?&gt;&lt;/h3&gt;
    &lt;?php endif ?&gt;

The most that can happen is that a user can relay a different code manually to get a different message to appear.

&gt; ** These 2 methods can be messed around with by the user *(harmlessly if you are scrubbing or controlling the output)* so that is why a cookie or session is better, but this is a pretty straight forward messaging method.

